      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im doing a lot of hiit lately and my legs feel like they are burning like crazy during the sprints. can u explain what is actually happening with the lactic acid in my muscles when that happens? and how does my body get rid of it after i stop?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When you're doing HIIT and your legs feel like they're burning during sprints, it's due to the accumulation of lactic acid in your muscles. Lactic acid is a byproduct of anaerobic respiration, where your muscles break down glucose to generate energy quickly, producing lactic acid as a waste product. This occurs when your muscles are working at high intensities for prolonged periods, causing your energy stores to be depleted rapidly. \n\nAs for getting rid of lactic acid, your body has two main methods: the removal of lactic acid through breathing (exhalation) and the removal through the bloodstream to the liver for breakdown. After you stop exercising, the lactic acid is slowly converted back into glucose in your liver, which can then be used for energy or stored as glycogen for future use.",
